{"term":"1963","caseName":"Platt v. Minnesota Mining & Manufacturing Company","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/1963/113","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - January 09, 1964 (Part 1)","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren11/oral_argument_audio/14242","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Number 113, Honorable Casper Platt, Petitioner, versus Minnesota Mining & Manufacturing Company.","start":0,"stop":27.837,"duration":27.84},{"text":"Mr. Friedman.","start":27.837,"stop":29.005,"duration":1.17}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel M. Friedman","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice and may it please the Court.","start":29.005,"stop":32.537,"duration":3.53},{"text":"This case which is here on a writ of certiorari to the Court of Appeals for the Seventh Circuit presents problems involving the use of the writ of mandamus to review the denial of an order entered under Rule 21 (b) of the Federal Rules of Criminal Procedure refusing to transfer the venue of a criminal case.","start":32.537,"stop":55.179,"duration":22.64},{"text":"Rule 21 (b) provides that where a crime has been committed in more than one district, the District Court where the indictment is filed upon the motion of the defendant shall transfer the case to another district where the suit might have been brought if the district judge is satisfied that this transfer would be in the interest of justice.","start":55.179,"stop":78.593,"duration":23.41}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":78.593,"stop":80.722,"duration":2.13}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel M. Friedman","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":80.722,"stop":80.918,"duration":0.2},{"text":"No, Mr. Justice --","start":80.918,"stop":81.209,"duration":0.29}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":81.209,"stop":82.004,"duration":0.8}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel M. Friedman","textObjs":[{"text":"-- this is a criminal case Rule 21 (b).","start":82.004,"stop":85.291,"duration":3.29}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- si that which might have been brought the business, I thought that was -- they're not --","start":85.291,"stop":88.848,"duration":3.56}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel M. Friedman","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":88.848,"stop":89.039,"duration":0.19},{"text":"That's not -- there's no -- there's no question in this case.","start":89.039,"stop":91.431,"duration":2.39},{"text":"Let me get this out of the way at the beginning, the Government conceded that this criminal action might have been brought in the District of Minnesota to its transferor's request.","start":91.431,"stop":100.463,"duration":9.03},{"text":"There's no way issue in this case of that.","start":100.463,"stop":102.988,"duration":2.53},{"text":"Question, it relates to the action of the District Court in refusing to transfer.","start":102.988,"stop":107.584,"duration":4.6},{"text":"Now in this case, a motion to transfer was scrupulous filed in the District Court in the Eastern District of Illinois where the indictment had been returned.","start":107.584,"stop":117.417,"duration":9.83},{"text":"The District Court after full consideration denied the motion ruling that it would be in the interest of justice for this case to be tried in the district there.","start":117.417,"stop":128.937,"duration":11.52},{"text":"The Court of Appeals for the Seventh Circuit concluded that one of ten factors which I'll come to in a moment which the District Court had relied on in denying the motion for transfer, was an improper fact.","start":128.937,"stop":143.636,"duration":14.7},{"text":"It then undertook to review the rest of the record without this one factor, concluded that without this one factor, this case should be transferred to the District of Minnesota and issued a writ of mandamus directing the petitioner Judge Platt to transfer the case.","start":143.636,"stop":161.902,"duration":18.27},{"text":"There are two basic issues in the case.","start":161.902,"stop":164.262,"duration":2.36},{"text":"First, the propriety of the Court of Appeals using the writ of mandamus at all to review this order and secondly, which is the principal issue that we've argued in our brief, assuming that the Court of Appeals was warranted in using the writ in these circumstances, did the Court of Appeals err when upon finding that one of the 10 factors relied upon was an erroneous one undertaking itself, itself to weigh these factors in concluding where the interest of justice lie.","start":164.262,"stop":195.211,"duration":30.95},{"text":"We contend that in the circumstances, assuming that writ was properly used when it found that there had been an improper factor relied on, it was obligatory on the Court of Appeals to remand this case to the District Court, to enable the district judge to re-exercise his discretion on the basis of the proper factors.","start":195.211,"stop":214.988,"duration":19.78},{"text":"I would like now to turn to the facts of the case --","start":214.988,"stop":217.566,"duration":2.58}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) if we find that mandamus is a proper, a proper (Inaudible).","start":217.566,"stop":223.049,"duration":5.48}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel M. Friedman","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct, Mr. Chief Justice.","start":223.049,"stop":224.664,"duration":1.61},{"text":"We asked it be sent back to the District Court to give him an opportunity to re-exercise his discretion.","start":224.664,"stop":230.371,"duration":5.71},{"text":"And I might -- may say that if it sent back to the District Court, we don't know without this one factor whether he will or will not retain the case.","start":230.371,"stop":238.356,"duration":7.98},{"text":"He may transfer it.","start":238.356,"stop":239.546,"duration":1.19},{"text":"He may retain it but we think he should be given another opportunity to exercise his discretion.","start":239.546,"stop":245.03,"duration":5.48}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":245.03,"stop":248.001,"duration":2.97}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel M. Friedman","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":248.001,"stop":249.173,"duration":1.17}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":249.173,"stop":257.219,"duration":8.05}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel M. Friedman","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the dis -- the district judge him --","start":257.219,"stop":258.675,"duration":1.46}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":258.675,"stop":262.979,"duration":4.3}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel M. Friedman","textObjs":[{"text":"The District Court judge said that this was in his response to the rule of show cause, he stated that this was just one of a number of factors.","start":262.979,"stop":269.818,"duration":6.84},{"text":"But we still think that the district judge should have an opportunity without this factor to reexamine the matter in con -- reaches his decision.","start":269.818,"stop":277.415,"duration":7.6}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":277.415,"stop":284.912,"duration":7.5}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel M. Friedman","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm not certain you -- I'm not certain Your Honor, I suspect he probably would but I think he should be given this opportunity.","start":284.912,"stop":291.771,"duration":6.86},{"text":"I like to turn to the facts and in my presentation of the facts what I shall attempt to show to the Court is basically that as this matter came before the District Court, there are arguments presented which admittedly favored transfer.","start":291.771,"stop":306.682,"duration":14.91},{"text":"Their arguments presented by the Government which militated against transfer and that this is an area where reasonable men might well differ as to whether this case should be transferred.","start":306.682,"stop":316.635,"duration":9.95},{"text":"We concede that.","start":316.635,"stop":317.949,"duration":1.31},{"text":"But the -- the District Court considered all of these factors and he concluded that on balance in the exercise of his discretion, it should not be transferred.","start":317.949,"stop":326.114,"duration":8.16}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) that no rights (Inaudible) go on and exercise his discretion.","start":326.114,"stop":333.223,"duration":7.11},{"text":"He used the All Writs Act to review that?","start":333.223,"stop":335.117,"duration":1.89}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel M. Friedman","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes -- let me say, explain that to point Mr. Justice.","start":335.117,"stop":338.089,"duration":2.97},{"text":"In our petition for certiorari, we did not raise any question with respect to the propriety of the use of the All Writs Act here.","start":338.089,"stop":346.2,"duration":8.11},{"text":"But upon further study of the case, we concluded that there is a really serious question as to whether the writ should be so used in this case and therefore we felt that appropriate to bring the matter before the Court but in view --","start":346.2,"stop":357.931,"duration":11.73}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Of course as I recall it in (Inaudible), we did recognize the availability of the All Writs Act to test, a -- the exercised discretion by a district judge.","start":357.931,"stop":368.312,"duration":10.38}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel M. Friedman","textObjs":[{"text":"But -- but that -- in that case Mr. Justice, involved a -- we think a quite different situation.","start":368.312,"stop":373.636,"duration":5.32}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"With the appointment of a Master but what I'm trying to get to is, do you question the availability of the All Writs Act?","start":373.636,"stop":379.127,"duration":5.49}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel M. Friedman","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":379.127,"stop":379.469,"duration":0.34},{"text":"We -- we don't --","start":379.469,"stop":379.64,"duration":0.17}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) discretion on the transfer.","start":379.64,"stop":381.625,"duration":1.99}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel M. Friedman","textObjs":[{"text":"We don't know, no.","start":381.625,"stop":383.014,"duration":1.39},{"text":"We don't question the -- the availability and we don't question the power of the Court of Appeals to exercise --","start":383.014,"stop":388.027,"duration":5.01}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"So that -- if it -- if the mandamus is available as a remedy, you also admit that it goes to reviewing the discretion of the district judge as well as its power.","start":388.027,"stop":400.831,"duration":12.8}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel M. Friedman","textObjs":[{"text":"I would say, if they're an abusive discretion, they were clear views of discretion.","start":400.831,"stop":405.408,"duration":4.58},{"text":"Well, let me give just as a hypothetical case --","start":405.408,"stop":407.229,"duration":1.82}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Alright, but you -- you -- you -- you will say that -- that that man -- that is a proper function of mandamus?","start":407.229,"stop":412.901,"duration":5.67},{"text":"You see, if the district judge has abused his discretion?","start":412.901,"stop":415.835,"duration":2.93}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel M. Friedman","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think -- I think it requires a great abuse of discretion for the writ to be exercised properly.","start":415.835,"stop":421.539,"duration":5.7},{"text":"I think if it's an -- if all that you have is that the reviewing court thinks the judge weighed the factors improperly, I don't think that is a proper exercise of it.","start":421.539,"stop":429.143,"duration":7.6}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) use of the word, exceptional (Inaudible).","start":429.143,"stop":432.03,"duration":2.89}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel M. Friedman","textObjs":[{"text":"Exceptional and this Court has repeatedly stressed the very limited function of the writ of mandamus in this area.","start":432.03,"stop":437.55,"duration":5.52}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"You might have had (Inaudible).","start":437.55,"stop":440.323,"duration":2.77}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel M. Friedman","textObjs":[{"text":"I think -- I think so.","start":440.323,"stop":441.326,"duration":1},{"text":"In other words, they deny -- there, the court had denied, he found the parties -- the Court held that the District Court in effect, had denied the parties, plaintiffs the right to trial by the court and remitted them to trial by with a Master.","start":441.326,"stop":451.933,"duration":10.61}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if the mandamus was available to get over that, your first point is that it didn't abuse his discretion.","start":451.933,"stop":459.011,"duration":7.08}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel M. Friedman","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we -- let me --","start":459.011,"stop":460.437,"duration":1.43}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap)","start":460.437,"stop":461.09,"duration":0.65}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel M. Friedman","textObjs":[{"text":"Let me put it a little differently if I may Mr. Justice.","start":461.09,"stop":464.474,"duration":3.38},{"text":"Our point is that mandamus is generally available but that any error in this case committed by the district judge does not seem to be the kind of error which is as appropriate to correct by an extraordinary writ at this interlocutory state, that's our point.","start":464.474,"stop":481.972,"duration":17.5},{"text":"Our second point is that assuming the Court of Appeals properly entered into it a disposition of the cases Your Honor.","start":481.972,"stop":487.624,"duration":5.65}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And the district judge was right.","start":487.624,"stop":490.48,"duration":2.86}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel M. Friedman","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":490.48,"stop":491.645,"duration":1.16},{"text":"We -- well, we-- we think the District Court -- district judge was right in denying the writ but we're suggesting that --","start":491.645,"stop":496.743,"duration":5.1}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":496.743,"stop":496.889,"duration":0.15}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel M. Friedman","textObjs":[{"text":"-- at a minimum, the Court of Appeals should have sent its back to the district judge.","start":496.889,"stop":499.508,"duration":2.62}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":499.508,"stop":499.647,"duration":0.14},{"text":"I understand.","start":499.647,"stop":501.064,"duration":1.42}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel M. Friedman","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, let me just briefly state some of these facts.","start":501.064,"stop":503.735,"duration":2.67}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":503.735,"stop":543.412,"duration":39.68}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel M. Friedman","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I -- I perhaps -- perhaps I am, I -- I think I don't know that this Court has ever specifically approved the use of mandamus to review it, an order of transfer but I can conceive of situations.","start":543.412,"stop":555.061,"duration":11.65},{"text":"I've give --give Your Honor one, there was a case in the Sixth Circuit some years ago where one district in the Circuit transferred a case to another district.","start":555.061,"stop":563.869,"duration":8.81},{"text":"The other district said that the first district was wrong and transferred it back again.","start":563.869,"stop":568.712,"duration":4.84},{"text":"Then the first district said to the second district, \"You had no business doing -- instruct the case from the docket.","start":568.712,"stop":573.48,"duration":4.77},{"text":"Well, it seems to me in that kind of situation involving a transfer order there must be some power in the appellate court to compel action there.","start":573.48,"stop":581.636,"duration":8.16},{"text":"Then, the indictment in this case was filed as I've indicated in the City of Danville in the Eastern District of Illinois, it charged Minnesota Mining and I shall refer to Minnesota Mining here by its colloquial name of 3M with violating Sections 1 and 2 of the Sherman Act.","start":581.636,"stop":600.003,"duration":18.37},{"text":"The indictment was in nine counts and there were three counts relating to each of three principal products of the company.","start":600.003,"stop":607.826,"duration":7.82},{"text":"In each of these three products that was charged that Minnesota Mining had conspired to monopolize, had attempted to monopolize and it conspired to restrain trade.","start":607.826,"stop":619.643,"duration":11.82},{"text":"The basic theory of the indictment, the whole, the unifying threat of the case is that what Minnesota Mining had done is had it used its patents with the threat of patent suits with the actual bring of patent suits to coerce its competitors into accepting licenses from Minnesota Mining which contained various restrictive provisions violative of the Sherman Act.","start":619.643,"stop":646.938,"duration":27.29},{"text":"The -- each of these nine counts charged that the offence committed has been conduct -- has been carried out in part within the Eastern District of Illinois.","start":646.938,"stop":658.691,"duration":11.75}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":658.691,"stop":664.536,"duration":5.84}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel M. Friedman","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the -- the --","start":664.536,"stop":665.294,"duration":0.76}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":665.294,"stop":672.358,"duration":7.06}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel M. Friedman","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it's hard to say Mr. Justice.","start":672.358,"stop":674.797,"duration":2.44},{"text":"The District Court in its opinion stated that without disclosure of the Government's evidence, you just couldn't tell where the majority of the patent negotiations had taken place.","start":674.797,"stop":688.06,"duration":13.26},{"text":"The Government's -- in its affidavit, the Government stated that -- that there were some negotiations at least one that took place within this district.","start":688.06,"stop":696.086,"duration":8.03},{"text":"They alleged that a large number of the patent negotiations did take place in the district.","start":696.086,"stop":700.781,"duration":4.69}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":700.781,"stop":727.26,"duration":26.48}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel M. Friedman","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, of course one thing Mr. Justice is, what we have here is a nationwide conspiracy.","start":727.26,"stop":732.209,"duration":4.95},{"text":"This is not just an allegation of a particular accident localized in a particular area.","start":732.209,"stop":737.537,"duration":5.33}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":737.537,"stop":774.702,"duration":37.16}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel M. Friedman","textObjs":[{"text":"If I may try to answer you -- two answers to that Mr. Justice.","start":774.702,"stop":779.02,"duration":4.32},{"text":"First, I suggest that the considerations which govern the forum for the trial of a major antitrust case maybe are somewhat different than those governed the trial of a negligent -- in an accident case.","start":779.02,"stop":792.178,"duration":13.16},{"text":"Secondly, I think that the -- as has been suggested that it is appropriate, the Government may choose the forum which it believes is the appropriate forum for bringing this case.","start":792.178,"stop":802.755,"duration":10.58},{"text":"Now, we brought the case in the District Court in Danville.","start":802.755,"stop":808.021,"duration":5.27},{"text":"The statute permitted us to bring the case in the --","start":808.021,"stop":811.742,"duration":3.72}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":811.742,"stop":836.696,"duration":24.95}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel M. Friedman","textObjs":[{"text":"Well I -- we're suggesting the -- that it does Mr. Justice.","start":836.696,"stop":840.026,"duration":3.33},{"text":"But it seems to me there's a basic fundamental distinction between these two cases.","start":840.026,"stop":843.533,"duration":3.51},{"text":"In the preceding case, the District Court in the exercise of his discretion, Judge Van Dusen concluded the transfer would be in the interest of justice.","start":843.533,"stop":852.563,"duration":9.03},{"text":"In this case, Judge Platt in the exercise of his discretion concluded the transfer would not be in the interest of justice.","start":852.563,"stop":861.248,"duration":8.69}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":861.248,"stop":867.04,"duration":5.79}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel M. Friedman","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I think -- I think --","start":867.04,"stop":867.862,"duration":0.82}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":867.862,"stop":868.665,"duration":0.8}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel M. Friedman","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":868.665,"stop":869.215,"duration":0.55}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":869.215,"stop":871.015,"duration":1.8}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel M. Friedman","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, Minnesota Mining in support of its motion to transfer filed nine affidavits of company officials and of its lawyers.","start":871.015,"stop":880.658,"duration":9.64},{"text":"And these -- these various affidavits set forth considerations which should make it more convenient to the company for the case to be tried in Minnesota and would make it less convenient to the company for the case to be tried in Danville.","start":880.658,"stop":895.503,"duration":14.85},{"text":"They pointed out that the headquarters were in the Eastern District of Minnesota in Saint Paul that will be easier for counsel during the trial of this lengthy case to confer with these officials in this district.","start":895.503,"stop":908.275,"duration":12.77},{"text":"They pointed out that it will be expense incurred in transferring the case because of the need to transport records, living expenses in Danville, various things and they also mentioned that according to the allegations in the indictment with they've been able to determine with one exception, no competitor resided in the Eastern District, no coconspirators resided in the Eastern District and that no meetings with alleged coconspirators took place there.","start":908.275,"stop":937.031,"duration":28.76},{"text":"Finally, they stressed that there would be no delay in the trial if it were transferred because they said the docket in Minnesota is current and the average case load for a judge in the District if Minnesota is less, slightly less than the average case load in the Eastern District of Illinois.","start":937.031,"stop":957.408,"duration":20.38},{"text":"The Government filed two affidavits in response, one of which was that of Mr. Jenkinson, the Head of our Midwest Office in the antitrust division, the Government's chief trial counsel.","start":957.408,"stop":968.25,"duration":10.84},{"text":"The affidavit first explained why this case was brought in the Eastern District of Illinois, pointed out the case had its inception when a complaint was received that had originated in the Eastern District of Illinois in East Saint Louis relating to one of these three products involved in this case.","start":968.25,"stop":986.58,"duration":18.33},{"text":"But after a preliminary investigation, the Government had been authorized to convene a grand jury to investigate this particular product and that -- as the investigation continued and the grand jury investigation lasted two years, complaints came in with respect to two other of these products involved and therefore the grand jury having gone and started the investigations expanded to cover all three products.","start":986.58,"stop":1010.932,"duration":24.35},{"text":"They also pointed out with respect to the burdens which 3M stated it would have to undergo if it was forced to try the case in Danville, that this company itself, had undertaken in the past to try a very substantial numbers in 35 patent infringement cases in districts far removed from its home office.","start":1010.932,"stop":1033.459,"duration":22.53},{"text":"Even though those who are -- many of those with cases in which venue might have been laid in the District if Minnesota that in the trial of these cases, this company brought a large number of witnesses, a large number of records, a large of attorneys to distant forums.","start":1033.459,"stop":1047.269,"duration":13.81},{"text":"And that indeed, Minnesota Mining had participated in one-four weeks trial of one of the patent cases involved in this very suit in the Eastern District of Illinois.","start":1047.269,"stop":1058.644,"duration":11.38},{"text":"Government also answered the claim of convenience of witnesses pointing out that within a 300 mile radius of Danville there were a substantial number of the Government's witnesses and that all within a 300 mile radius of Saint Paul, only one or two minor Government witnesses lived.","start":1058.644,"stop":1078.249,"duration":19.61},{"text":"And furthermore, that a majority of the Government's key witnesses would find Danville substantially more convenient than Minnesota.","start":1078.249,"stop":1087.196,"duration":8.95},{"text":"The Government also stated that patent license negotiations had taken place in Danville and that a number of residents of the Eastern District -- I might correct that, had taken place in the Eastern District, the patent of negotiation not in Danville.","start":1087.196,"stop":1099.738,"duration":12.54},{"text":"And that a number of residents of that district would be Government witnesses.","start":1099.738,"stop":1103.205,"duration":3.47},{"text":"Finally, the Government stressed and we think this is important because one of the grounds upon which Judge Platt relied into denying transfer was that trial in Danville would result in trial a year sooner than in the District of Minnesota.","start":1103.205,"stop":1118.632,"duration":15.43},{"text":"That attempting to determine the likelihood of a speedy trial, on the basis of testing the average number of cases per judge in each of the district, was not a fair gauge to Judge Platt's docket.","start":1118.632,"stop":1132.032,"duration":13.4},{"text":"And this was because in the District of Minnesota which has one district, there are four judges and the cases are rotated among the four judges.","start":1132.032,"stop":1140.865,"duration":8.83},{"text":"Whereas in the Eastern District of Illinois, there are two judges, one sitting in East Saint Louis, Judge Jergens and Judge Platt sitting in the other division in Danville.","start":1140.865,"stop":1154.319,"duration":13.45},{"text":"And most of the 327 cases which were pending in the Eastern District were pending before Judge Jergens and would be tried before Judge Jergens.","start":1154.319,"stop":1164.363,"duration":10.04},{"text":"And the total number of cases pending before Judge Platt was a total of 109 civil or two -- and two criminal cases which this was one, for a total of a 111 cases as against an average of the four judges in the District of Minnesota of 170.","start":1164.363,"stop":1182.385,"duration":18.02},{"text":"And they also pointed out information from the clerk of the District Court in Minnesota that the customary practice in that district is a criminal case with a non-natural defendant is put of the end of the calendar.","start":1182.385,"stop":1196.021,"duration":13.64},{"text":"And the clerk's office indicated that if this case were transferred to the District of Minnesota, it probably be at least a year until the case could be brought in trial.","start":1196.021,"stop":1208.148,"duration":12.13},{"text":"Extensive briefs were filed on this motion.","start":1208.148,"stop":1210.88,"duration":2.73},{"text":"Judge Platt heard two days of oral argument and the court denied transfer.","start":1210.88,"stop":1216.677,"duration":5.8},{"text":"The judge draws a lengthy memorandum in which he discussed separately 10 factors which the defendant had urged as a basis to transfer.","start":1216.677,"stop":1226.751,"duration":10.07},{"text":"He took each one of them up.","start":1226.751,"stop":1227.856,"duration":1.11},{"text":"He found that some of them definitely favored transfer that others militated against transfer.","start":1227.856,"stop":1234.065,"duration":6.21},{"text":"He pointed out that while it would be convenience to the plaintiff -- to the defendant if the case were tried in Saint Paul.","start":1234.065,"stop":1240.867,"duration":6.8},{"text":"There would also be great convenience to the Government and he took up each one of these factors, found some of them, pro-transfer some of whom against the factor.","start":1240.867,"stop":1249.785,"duration":8.92},{"text":"After discussing the nine factors which are the -- might say the traditional criteria which courts have customarily looked to in passing on transfer motions, he came to a section called, special factors of hardship.","start":1249.785,"stop":1262.975,"duration":13.19},{"text":"And one of the factors he said was that in view of the position which Minnesota Mining had achieved in the community, in view of the substantial number of stockholders and employees who reside on that district, it would be more difficult to get a fair and impartial jury in the District of Minnesota than in the Eastern of District of Illinois.","start":1262.975,"stop":1285.427,"duration":22.45},{"text":"The --","start":1285.427,"stop":1285.831,"duration":0.4}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1285.831,"stop":1287.779,"duration":1.95}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel M. Friedman","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":1287.779,"stop":1288.039,"duration":0.26},{"text":"We do not -- we do not challenge that ruling.","start":1288.039,"stop":1292.589,"duration":4.55},{"text":"Minnesota Mining sought a writ of mandamus from the Seventh Circuit, asking the court to require the transfer, and it's stated in its petition that in refusing to transfer, Judge Platt had denied it the right trial in it's home district namely as they said -- mainly on the ground that the Government could not obtain a fair trial in the District of Minnesota.","start":1292.589,"stop":1317.639,"duration":25.05},{"text":"Judge Platt filed a personally signed response to the rule to show cause that it issued.","start":1317.639,"stop":1322.649,"duration":5.01},{"text":"And in this response, he said that that was not the soul of the main ground.","start":1322.649,"stop":1326.627,"duration":3.98},{"text":"He said that there are number of other factors which also militated against transfer.","start":1326.627,"stop":1331.927,"duration":5.3},{"text":"And he said, I've set them out in my memorandum, he reiterated them.","start":1331.927,"stop":1336.201,"duration":4.27},{"text":"He pointed out that he had considered the fact that the headquarters of this company was in Saint Paul, as one of the factors to be evaluated.","start":1336.201,"stop":1345.107,"duration":8.91},{"text":"But he said he didn't find it all controlling.","start":1345.107,"stop":1347.714,"duration":2.61},{"text":"He also indicated reasons which in his judgment suggested that the burdens upon 3M in to having to go to Danville would not be as great as they had suggested.","start":1347.714,"stop":1360.024,"duration":12.31},{"text":"A divided, a sharply divided Seventh Circuit Court of Appeals granted the writ.","start":1360.024,"stop":1365.169,"duration":5.15},{"text":"It said that Judge Platt had erred in considering this factor of the Government's difficulty of obtaining an impartial jury in Minneapolis and he said in addition, the case was impressed with the fundamental historical right of defendant to be prosecuted in its own environment or district.","start":1365.169,"stop":1381.385,"duration":16.22},{"text":"It then itself undertook to review the record and concluded that without this single factor, the interest of justice favored the transfer.","start":1381.385,"stop":1390.965,"duration":9.58},{"text":"Judge -- Chief Judge Hastings in dissent disagreed with the Court of Appeals on both grounds.","start":1390.965,"stop":1396.105,"duration":5.14},{"text":"He thought that there had not been shown an abuse of discretion and certainly not such an abuse of discretion is -- warrant an extraordinary writ.","start":1396.105,"stop":1403.182,"duration":7.08},{"text":"He also said the majority had made an unprecedented procedural error in itself undertaking to balance the interest in deciding where the interest of justice lie rather than sending it back to the District Court.","start":1403.182,"stop":1417.328,"duration":14.15},{"text":"Now, I'd like just briefly -- we've developed it in our brief to advert to the question of whether the writ of mandamus was properly employed at all here.","start":1417.328,"stop":1426.109,"duration":8.78},{"text":"This claim has frequently pointed out the limited office of the writ.","start":1426.109,"stop":1429.907,"duration":3.8},{"text":"It is not intended as a substitute for appeal that it is limited to correcting a gross abuse of discretion to confining a District Court to the exercise of its proper discretion or to compelling a court to act when action was withheld.","start":1429.907,"stop":1447.742,"duration":17.84},{"text":"And we think that even conceding that 1 of the 10 factors should not have been taken into account by the District Judge, the mere lives in 1 of 10 does not rise to the level, the kind of abuse which would warrant review of this interlocutory order through the extraordinary writ.","start":1447.742,"stop":1467.509,"duration":19.77},{"text":"Now to be sure there are some basic distinctions that maybe drawn between the use of the -- the writ in a criminal case to review a transfer order and to review -- and the use in the civil case, the most obvious one is that there is no Interlocutory Appeals Act available in a criminal case.","start":1467.509,"stop":1483.686,"duration":16.18},{"text":"On the one hand, this perhaps -- this does show that there's no alternative remedy available by which a litigant may test the transfer order.","start":1483.686,"stop":1491.717,"duration":8.03},{"text":"But conversely, it seems to us that this also suggest that and -- and underlines the strong policy to which this Court has frequently adverted and fairly recently in the Di Bella case that we should not have piecemeal appeals in criminal cases.","start":1491.717,"stop":1510.9,"duration":19.18},{"text":"That criminal cases the -- the importance of a speedy trial overcomes the possibility that a litigant maybe forced to go through a trial and that an error or -- or with a preliminary error which would ultimately infect the proceedings and be cause for reversal.","start":1510.9,"stop":1526.849,"duration":15.95},{"text":"Now also, I -- I think that I should quite frankly state that it will undoubtedly be more difficult after conviction if there was a conviction to review the discretionary action of a District Court in denying transfer, because basically in these cases transfer is sought on the theory that it's less convenient to be tried in the other forum.","start":1526.849,"stop":1549.399,"duration":22.55},{"text":"And once the trial is over, it will be very difficult to say that the fact that I was inconvenienced is a ground for reversal.","start":1549.399,"stop":1556.621,"duration":7.22},{"text":"But again, it seems to me, this also cuts two ways that the fact that it's unlikely to be prej -- sufficiently prejudicial to call for reversal, suggests that it's not the kind of thing that should be reviewed on extraordinary writ.","start":1556.621,"stop":1573.072,"duration":16.45},{"text":"The rule in the case Rule 21 (b), we think makes it quite clear despite its terms that this is a matter for the discretion of the District Court.","start":1573.072,"stop":1583.521,"duration":10.45},{"text":"It speaks -- use -- the language it uses say that should be a transfer if the Court is satisfied that in the interest of justice, the case should be transferred.","start":1583.521,"stop":1591.407,"duration":7.89},{"text":"The Court is satisfied.","start":1591.407,"stop":1592.517,"duration":1.11},{"text":"It puts it up.","start":1592.517,"stop":1593.46,"duration":0.94},{"text":"The District Court has to be satisfied.","start":1593.46,"stop":1595.329,"duration":1.87},{"text":"The interest of justice is a very broad threat.","start":1595.329,"stop":1599.048,"duration":3.72},{"text":"It doesn't set out particularities.","start":1599.048,"stop":1601.491,"duration":2.44},{"text":"You don't decide whether a transfer was in the interest of justice by a mathematical process of adding up the factors in favor and the factors against and subtracting one from the other and see where the balance is.","start":1601.491,"stop":1612.969,"duration":11.48},{"text":"The -- the intangibles involved in making this decision seems to us the kind of thing that necessarily is committed to the discretion of the District Court.","start":1612.969,"stop":1622.039,"duration":9.07},{"text":"And not surprisingly not in view of the statute, this language, the revisers, the Advisory Committee explicitly stated in describing this provision that -- it said that after pointing out the previous -- to Rule 21 (b), there had no been -- been no provision for transfer of venue in criminal cases.","start":1622.039,"stop":1638.779,"duration":16.74},{"text":"It stated the matter will now be left in the discretion of the Court.","start":1638.779,"stop":1644.252,"duration":5.47},{"text":"Now, the defendants stressed and they've urged repeatedly that basically, the reason Judge Platt was wrong here apart from this single fact and the reason why that this Court of Appeals correctly directed transfer was, they say they have a -- some historical right to have a right to be tried at their own residence.","start":1644.252,"stop":1667.305,"duration":23.05},{"text":"And that this Court has recognized in construing venue statutes that there is a policy favoring trial at the residence of the defendant.","start":1667.305,"stop":1675.338,"duration":8.03},{"text":"But we think when you're dealing with the transfer statute where admittedly the case might have been brought in any one of the number of venues, that the significance of trial at the residence of the defendant is no more than a shorthand phrase for the various advantages, which will flow if a defendant is tried where its more convenient to him.","start":1675.338,"stop":1697.965,"duration":22.63},{"text":"In a case of a corporation, admittedly in some cases there'd be very substantial advantages to being tried at the home or in other cases, there might not be.","start":1697.965,"stop":1706.147,"duration":8.18},{"text":"If the conduct that was challenged in the criminal case involve primarily the officials at a branch office and the records were there I presume the most convenient form would be where that branch office is located.","start":1706.147,"stop":1719.16,"duration":13.01},{"text":"But, we think the important thing in this is that the District Court did consider under the rubric of the interest of justice, all of the factors which the district, which the defendants relied on as justifying and calling for transfer to their home forum and found that these advantages were outweighed and were not -- that the defendants had not shown, had not made the showing that the transfer would be in the interest of justice.","start":1719.16,"stop":1744.736,"duration":25.58},{"text":"We think it clear that mandamus cannot be used to tell the District Court how to exercise its discretions but only to require the District Court to conduct itself and exercise the discretion in accordance with the proper standards.","start":1744.736,"stop":1758.757,"duration":14.02}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1758.757,"stop":1761.845,"duration":3.09}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel M. Friedman","textObjs":[{"text":"This is a Delaware Corporation with its principal --","start":1761.845,"stop":1764.685,"duration":2.84}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1764.685,"stop":1766.688,"duration":2}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel M. Friedman","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1766.688,"stop":1766.798,"duration":0.11},{"text":"I -- I suppose so.","start":1766.798,"stop":1768.076,"duration":1.28},{"text":"It's -- but -- but its main office concededly as in Saint Paul.","start":1768.076,"stop":1772.019,"duration":3.94},{"text":"Thank you.","start":1772.019,"stop":1772.815,"duration":0.8}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1772.815,"stop":1776.038,"duration":3.22}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel M. Friedman","textObjs":[{"text":"Well as I indicated Mr. -- Mr. Justice, the reason is that the invest -- a com -- the case originated from a complaint that was received from the Eastern District of Illinois that the invest the grand jury was convened in that district which is not an unusual practice in antitrust cases and that was where the case developed.","start":1776.038,"stop":1798.342,"duration":22.3}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"We'll recess now.","start":1798.342,"stop":1800.321,"duration":1.98}]}]},{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - January 09, 1964 (Part 2)","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren11/oral_argument_audio/14584","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chadwell, you may proceed with your argument.","start":0,"stop":5.12,"duration":5.12}]},{"speakerName":"John T. Chadwell","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.","start":5.12,"stop":14.506,"duration":9.39},{"text":"The Court of Appeals of the Seventh Circuit issued its writ of mandamus in this case, may it please the Court.","start":14.506,"stop":23.353,"duration":8.85},{"text":"The cause in the opinion of the Court of Appeals, the record facts show a clear abuse of discretion on the part of the District Court in denying our motion to transfer this complex antitrust case from Danville where the Government chose to bring the case to St. Paul.","start":23.353,"stop":48.784,"duration":25.43},{"text":"From Danville, where the defendant has no office, plant, facility or employee, to Minnesota, where it has its main office, all employees, officers or directors who know anything about this, the issues in this case, where the Government has not alleged or stated in a single affidavit, contrary to what Mr. Friedman inadvertently stated, that a single witness, a single witness resides within the District -- Eastern District of Illinois.","start":48.784,"stop":92.968,"duration":44.18},{"text":"The Court of Appeals made its decision upon three -- that the Court had -- had clearly abused its discretion on the basis of three primary considerations.","start":92.968,"stop":107.677,"duration":14.71},{"text":"The first of which, as I understood Mr. Freedman today, he admits to have been improper.","start":107.677,"stop":113.788,"duration":6.11},{"text":"The first was that it was unlikely that the Government could secure a fair trial in Minnesota and admitted that that was an improper factor.","start":113.788,"stop":124.161,"duration":10.37},{"text":"That was one reason that the Court of Appeals thought that the District Court has abused its discretion.","start":124.161,"stop":130.204,"duration":6.04},{"text":"The second reason was that the denial of transfer was ordered despite the public policy sometimes referred to or referred to in the Johnson case as the constitutional concern of the courts for try out of a criminal case in the home district of the defendant in the absence of strong reasons to the contrary.","start":130.204,"stop":160.789,"duration":30.58},{"text":"And the third reason why the Court of Appeals thought that this was a clear abuse of discretion was that there was every reason for a trial in the home district of the defendant, St. Paul, Minnesota or the District of Minnesota, add no substantial reason for a trial in the Eastern District of Illinois.","start":160.789,"stop":185.954,"duration":25.17},{"text":"Now, why the Government chose to present this matter to a grand jury in the Eastern District of Illinois in Danville some 130 miles or so South of Chicago, why they did it?","start":185.954,"stop":201.435,"duration":15.48},{"text":"We don't know.","start":201.435,"stop":202.816,"duration":1.38},{"text":"We know the explanation they gave, this we do know.","start":202.816,"stop":207.539,"duration":4.72},{"text":"They did it in spite of the fact that they had to come to St. Paul over a period of something like 17 years intermittently.","start":207.539,"stop":217.753,"duration":10.21},{"text":"This investigation started back in 1945.","start":217.753,"stop":221.721,"duration":3.97},{"text":"It was quite active for a number of years then there was a period when it wasn't and then it was resumed and there -- there, it went on for a long period of time.","start":221.721,"stop":230.405,"duration":8.68},{"text":"They spent weeks and months in the offices of the company at St. Paul.","start":230.405,"stop":235.705,"duration":5.3},{"text":"They knew all about the fact that St. Paul was the situs of this whole thing, yet they choose to proceed in Danville.","start":235.705,"stop":243.466,"duration":7.76},{"text":"I say I don't know why they did, they did.","start":243.466,"stop":245.964,"duration":2.5},{"text":"We don't have to show that they shouldn't have proceeded in Danville.","start":245.964,"stop":248.506,"duration":2.54},{"text":"All we have to show under Rule 21 (b) is that we come within that rule after the indictment was return.","start":248.506,"stop":258.541,"duration":10.03},{"text":"And on that, if Your Honors please, I would like to make a brief statement about the provisions and purposes of Rule 21 (b).","start":258.541,"stop":272.164,"duration":13.62},{"text":"Rule 21 (b) differs from Section 1404 (a) which this Court has -- had before it in the preceding case.","start":272.164,"stop":281.407,"duration":9.24},{"text":"In that it, of course, that is Rule 21 (b), is a rule of this Court under the criminal rules of Rules of Criminal Procedure.","start":281.407,"stop":290.314,"duration":8.91},{"text":"This Section 1404 (a), of course, is a statute.","start":290.314,"stop":295.853,"duration":5.54},{"text":"It has also one additional significant, a difference in phraseology, I would submit and that is that Rule 1404 (a) is permissive.","start":295.853,"stop":307.97,"duration":12.12},{"text":"It says the Court may transfer, may transfer where the -- where the circumstances come within the provisions of the rule.","start":307.97,"stop":318.775,"duration":10.8},{"text":"In rule -- in this statute, in Rule 21 (b), the provision is that the Court shall transfer where it appears that in the interest of justice, a transfer should be made to another district in which a venue lies.","start":318.775,"stop":338.338,"duration":19.56},{"text":"Now, there is no doubt that the Court is vested with discretion of course in passing upon a motion of this kind and is entitled to way, what is said by the moving party in this case, Minnesota Mining, as against what it said by the Government, by a way of bill of particulars, allegations of the indictment or affidavits.","start":338.338,"stop":363.72,"duration":25.38},{"text":"But, if the trial court, passing on this motion, is unable to make a finding as to a single substantial reason why the case should not be transferred, then it is clearly a case of abuse of discretion and one which the Court of Appeals properly should've issued as it did, their writ of mandamus.","start":363.72,"stop":392.12,"duration":28.4},{"text":"Now on that point, I would like to state that the basic purpose of this rule, which has been recognized in a number of lower court decisions, this being the first time the case involving the rule directly has been before Your Honors, the basic purpose of this rule has been to reach this precise sort of a case.","start":392.12,"stop":417.231,"duration":25.11},{"text":"As a matter of fact, Judge Holtzoff, who was Secretary of the Advisory Committee, and Judge Medallia, who was a member of the Advisory Committee, each have made statements, which are referred to in our brief on the different seminars and so on shortly after the rules were adopted in which they stated that one of the principle reasons that the Advisory Committee recommended Rule 21 (b) to the Supreme Court was because of the practice followed.","start":417.231,"stop":444.623,"duration":27.39},{"text":"In the past, in the Antitrust Division of the United States Department of Justice in bringing criminal antitrust cases away from the home district of the defendant.","start":444.623,"stop":457.266,"duration":12.64},{"text":"That's exactly what these two judges, who were members of the committee, said and that is what the lower courts have recognized to have been a basic purpose of this rule when the Supreme Court adopted it.","start":457.266,"stop":471.838,"duration":14.57},{"text":"Now, the fact of the matter is, if Your Honor please -- Your Honors please, we do not argue that the defendant has an absolute right.","start":471.838,"stop":481.091,"duration":9.25},{"text":"We do not argue that the defendant has an absolute right to transfer to its home district.","start":481.091,"stop":486.123,"duration":5.03},{"text":"We do argue that that right of trial in the home district is recognized in Rule 21 (b) was a reason why it was adopted and that in the absence of reasons to the contrary, substantial reasons to the contrary, transfers should take place, should be ordered.","start":486.123,"stop":506.994,"duration":20.87},{"text":"And I -- I call to the Court's attention this fact that until Judge Platt denied transfer in this criminal case, not a single District Court and not a single Court of Appeals had refused to transfer a criminal antitrust case to the home district of the defendant or to a branch office of the defendant if the facts took place there rather than in the home district on motion of the defendant.","start":506.994,"stop":539.36,"duration":32.37},{"text":"The latter sort of a situation, the home -- the -- the branch office residence or situs of the defendant -- of a defendant is the General Motors case, which we cite in our brief.","start":539.36,"stop":551.936,"duration":12.58},{"text":"And I might say to Your Honors that we collect the cases on page 39 to 40 in our brief.","start":551.936,"stop":558.549,"duration":6.61},{"text":"Those cases bear out what I'm just saying to the Court.","start":558.549,"stop":561.147,"duration":2.6},{"text":"Now in the General Motors case, we had a situation that would've been similar to what we would've had here if at -- if at Danville, there'd been a branch office of Minnesota Mining, let us say and if the activities of the defendant related to that branch office.","start":561.147,"stop":578.108,"duration":16.96},{"text":"In General Motors, the locomotive case, electromotive case was brought against -- was brought against them in -- in New York, indictment was there.","start":578.108,"stop":589.144,"duration":11.04},{"text":"A move to transfer to Chicago and not Detroit because in Chicago, the locomotive division had its headquarters, the books and records were there, the witnesses were there and that in the interest of justice, it was contended and held by the District Court, should be the place of trial.","start":589.144,"stop":605.705,"duration":16.56},{"text":"That was where it was removed to.","start":605.705,"stop":607.239,"duration":1.53},{"text":"Now here, if Danville had been an area where there was a -- an important branch office or a branch office of this company or the activities had substantially taking place there, a great many of the witnesses were there, then of course, Danville would've been a proper situs for the trial of this case.","start":607.239,"stop":627.72,"duration":20.48},{"text":"But as I said, there's not a thing that connects this company with --with Danville except, except that the defendant -- that the Government claims that in Danville, they can prove venue.","start":627.72,"stop":642.097,"duration":14.38},{"text":"And venue they set forth in here as the most minimal amount and as Your Honors know, it is not required to show very much in order to prove venue.","start":642.097,"stop":650.557,"duration":8.46},{"text":"Well, assuming that they can prove venue, that is when Rule 21 comes into play.","start":650.557,"stop":657.192,"duration":6.63},{"text":"It's admitted for the purposes of this motion that venue was properly laid in Danville, that gives them no right to keep it there, that would be exercising the right to an absolute choice of forum which is the right that the Government had prior to the adoption of Rule 21 (b).","start":657.192,"stop":674.975,"duration":17.78},{"text":"If an indictment came down in a certain district and if venue lay there, there's nothing that could be done about it.","start":674.975,"stop":682.738,"duration":7.76},{"text":"Now, the Court has recognized the injustices stated by Judge Medallia, a member of the Advisory Committee, that existed prior to the adoption of Rule 21 (b) and has said that under these circumstances where it is in the interest of justice, a criminal case shall be transferred, shall be transferred to another district where venue lies.","start":682.738,"stop":707.656,"duration":24.92},{"text":"And I -- I urge to the Court that the facts here support the Court of Appeals completely and that there's no substantial reason why the case should've been kept in Danville.","start":707.656,"stop":724.02,"duration":16.36},{"text":"And with the Court's permission, I should like to review therefore the factual considerations, which caused me, if Your Honors please, to make that statement.","start":724.02,"stop":734.553,"duration":10.53},{"text":"The first is this.","start":734.553,"stop":736.657,"duration":2.1},{"text":"I've already said it.","start":736.657,"stop":738.915,"duration":2.26},{"text":"The home office, research laboratories, number of these manufacturing plants, all its records are in St. Paul.","start":738.915,"stop":745.861,"duration":6.95},{"text":"No office, plant, branch or employee in the Eastern District of Illinois.","start":745.861,"stop":750.042,"duration":4.18},{"text":"All officers in the company live in St. Paul or near St. Paul, none in the Eastern District of Illinois.","start":750.042,"stop":756.662,"duration":6.62},{"text":"The defendant's uncontradicted affidavits show that all officers and employees of the company, called before the grand jury during the extensive period of this investigation, came from St. Paul except one man who had retired and had previously lived in St. Paul and was then living in California.","start":756.662,"stop":780.307,"duration":23.64},{"text":"Everyone that the -- the fact is that the defendant has shown by affidavit that other witnesses known to the defendant, they were able to determine from appearances before the grand jury and the like, 24 of the employees of alleged co-conspirators come from the East Coast to which East Coast or Chicago not a one from Danville or in St. Paul.","start":780.307,"stop":815.427,"duration":35.12},{"text":"They come from the East Coast, Chicago or St. Paul, none from the Danville area.","start":815.427,"stop":823.229,"duration":7.8},{"text":"The -- the District Court did say that obviously, if Your Honors will read his opinion, that obviously, St. Paul would be more convenient for the defense witnesses than Danville and made that finding which of course was obvious.","start":823.229,"stop":843.137,"duration":19.91},{"text":"But he said as to the Government witnesses, and I quote, The question of convenience is not so easily determined.","start":843.137,"stop":851.211,"duration":8.07},{"text":"Now, he hadn't make a single finding, as indeed he could not, that it would be more convenient for the Government witnesses.","start":851.211,"stop":857.83,"duration":6.62},{"text":"He merely said it's not easy to determine it.","start":857.83,"stop":859.864,"duration":2.03},{"text":"And the reason it wasn't easy to determine it was because that the Government refused to give him any information from which he could make the determination except the general affidavit that they had a substantial number of witnesses who were within the 300-mile radius of the East District of Illinois, didn't say within the East District of Illinois, within 300 miles and they would be inconvenience by going to St. Paul rather than Danville where the 300 -- that's the conclusion of the find.","start":859.864,"stop":885.906,"duration":26.04},{"text":"In fact, the matter is that 300 miles in Danville include Chicago, and our affidavit show that it is much easier to get from Chicago to St. Paul as it -- than from Chicago to Danville.","start":885.906,"stop":900.146,"duration":14.24},{"text":"The error time on jets to St. Paul is about the same as the airtime from Chicago to -- to Danville approximately an hour in each instance.","start":900.146,"stop":910.841,"duration":10.7},{"text":"And then the frequency of the flights are much greater in the instance in the case of Chicago to St. Paul than from Chicago to Danville.","start":910.841,"stop":922.325,"duration":11.48},{"text":"Now, I say that the Government has a right to refuse to give any information on the facts in -- in contesting one of these motions.","start":922.325,"stop":931.774,"duration":9.45},{"text":"But one of the consequences of their failure to do so, I respectively submit, is that they're going to lose the motion because if they're unwilling to give any facts even without naming witnesses their location, how can they expect the Court to make any finding?","start":931.774,"stop":947.888,"duration":16.11},{"text":"Court can't make any finding and indeed Judge Platt didn't on that point which found that it's not so easy to determine the convenience of the Government witnesses.","start":947.888,"stop":958.507,"duration":10.62},{"text":"Well, assuming that the convenience of the Government witnesses should override the convenience of the defense, and I say in a criminal case that should not be the case, there is no finding against us on that point whatsoever.","start":958.507,"stop":973.179,"duration":14.67},{"text":"And I say that even though -- there -- it would be convenient for a number of the Government witnesses to go St. -- to go to Danville rather than St. Paul, that fact should not weigh a penny weight unless it's an overwhelming showing in view of the very strong showing that we have made here as to the convenience of our witnesses.","start":973.179,"stop":995.06,"duration":21.88},{"text":"We have shown by uncontradicted affidavits that the cost to us for trying this case in -- in Danville above the cost of try -- for trying the case in Minnesota would be over $100,000.","start":995.06,"stop":1010.945,"duration":15.89},{"text":"No dispute on that whatsoever and it is perfectly obvious.","start":1010.945,"stop":1013.836,"duration":2.89},{"text":"That's a minimum figure I might say that we gave in the -- in the affidavit.","start":1013.836,"stop":1018.174,"duration":4.34},{"text":"And another point that we make which the Court of Appeals referred to in the opinion that it's obvious, of course, to -- to the Justices of this Court, is that in defending a complex criminal case of this kind.","start":1018.174,"stop":1035.367,"duration":17.19},{"text":"And as a reason for the home district rule, it is of the utmost importance for trial counsel to have constant immediate access to -- to officials, employees and -- and records of the defendant company.","start":1035.367,"stop":1052.662,"duration":17.3},{"text":"Now, I submit to the Court that this is far more important in a criminal case than in a civil case.","start":1052.662,"stop":1060.723,"duration":8.06},{"text":"We have tried, of course, those of us involved in -- in a good deal of antitrust litigation, have tried a great many civil cases away from the home of the home office of the defendant.","start":1060.723,"stop":1073.631,"duration":12.91},{"text":"Where do you have pretrial discovery, you're able to get the records of the Government or the opponent, you're able to find out about the witnesses, you can take depositions.","start":1073.631,"stop":1084.482,"duration":10.85},{"text":"And when the trial starts, you're pretty well set and you know what employees or officers of the defendant company should be at the situs of the trial, you know that from your pre-trial discovery.","start":1084.482,"stop":1097.197,"duration":12.71},{"text":"There is no pretrial discovery in this criminal cases, is a strong reason for the applicability of Rule 21 (b) here.","start":1097.197,"stop":1105.91,"duration":8.71},{"text":"I submit to Your Honors, if we had to try this complex case in Danville, which our record -- which our affidavit show will take four or five or six months to try, it's a matter involving the three separate product lines of this company, very important product lines.","start":1105.91,"stop":1124.854,"duration":18.94},{"text":"They're claiming that we filed 44 patent suits or defendant 44 patent suits over a period of 25 years and our good faith in our patent activities is at issue.","start":1124.854,"stop":1138.817,"duration":13.96},{"text":"If we had to try this case in Danville, we would not have the slightest idea in advance of trial just who we ought to have down there and who we shouldn't.","start":1138.817,"stop":1148.821,"duration":10},{"text":"It could very well be.","start":1148.821,"stop":1150.13,"duration":1.31},{"text":"We don't know the names of these witnesses.","start":1150.13,"stop":1152.047,"duration":1.92},{"text":"We don't know what the Government's going to say.","start":1152.047,"stop":1153.931,"duration":1.88},{"text":"We're not permitted to have pretrial discovery.","start":1153.931,"stop":1156.558,"duration":2.63},{"text":"It could very well be.But we get into court, we start the trial of this case, they will call to the stand some witness that I had never heard of.","start":1156.558,"stop":1167.038,"duration":10.48},{"text":"And how do I find out why I go to the -- to the people in the Minnesota Mining who has had to do with that transaction to find out?","start":1167.038,"stop":1176.525,"duration":9.49},{"text":"And I -- and I find that they we're -- he's up in St. Paul, we didn't know we're going to need him down here in Danville, so we didn't bring him down.","start":1176.525,"stop":1185.23,"duration":8.7},{"text":"Now, what about the record?","start":1185.23,"stop":1187.628,"duration":2.4},{"text":"Well, they're up in St. Paul.","start":1187.628,"stop":1190.214,"duration":2.59},{"text":"Now, that's undenied.","start":1190.214,"stop":1192.172,"duration":1.96},{"text":"There's no question what I'm stating to the Court from beginning to end here is undenied in the record in this case.","start":1192.172,"stop":1199.531,"duration":7.36},{"text":"Is it -- is it in the interest of justice under Rule 21 (b)?","start":1199.531,"stop":1204.786,"duration":5.26},{"text":"Is it within the discretion of a trial court?","start":1204.786,"stop":1207.817,"duration":3.03},{"text":"Were these facts are admitted, conceded, undenied?","start":1207.817,"stop":1212.637,"duration":4.82},{"text":"That the trial court should say, Oh, well, maybe you can't defend this case as well in Danville\", but the Government says, as the trial court said here, that they've got some records in St. Paul and they'd have to send him up to Minneapolis.","start":1212.637,"stop":1226.129,"duration":13.49},{"text":"Well, I'll tell you what records they've got in St. Paul.","start":1226.129,"stop":1228.646,"duration":2.52},{"text":"They've got some records that they subpoenaed from various people in this case.","start":1228.646,"stop":1232.434,"duration":3.79}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) Danville, right?","start":1232.434,"stop":1233.223,"duration":0.79}]},{"speakerName":"John T. Chadwell","textObjs":[{"text":"I said Dan -- I'm sorry.","start":1233.223,"stop":1234.374,"duration":1.15},{"text":"In -- in Danville, they have some records that they subpoenaed from various witnesses who appeared before the grand jury and according to the size and weight of the boxes that they describe, it had cost $50 for them to send these records from -- from Danville up to St. Paul.","start":1234.374,"stop":1250.783,"duration":16.41},{"text":"The -- the Court, the District Court took note, took note of our contention, which I am making to Your Honors here, that we need a constant access to the record in the people in Minnesota Mining to defend this complex criminal case where we had no discovery prior to trial.","start":1250.783,"stop":1271.243,"duration":20.46},{"text":"He -- he recognized that but he said in view of the size of the defendant that should not make too much difference.","start":1271.243,"stop":1278.241,"duration":7},{"text":"Well, as the Court of Appeals said in -- in dealing with that subject, if Your Honors please, it does make a difference.","start":1278.241,"stop":1286.809,"duration":8.57},{"text":"And I would like to read to the Court from the opinion of the Court of Appeals on the facts, the facts of this case aside from the concededly improper factor, namely, the fair trial in Minnesota issue, concededly an improper.","start":1286.809,"stop":1303.535,"duration":16.73},{"text":"Aside from that, the Court found that there was no substantial reason to hold this case in Danville and here is what the Court said and I am reading from -- from page 248 of the record, if Your Honors please.","start":1303.535,"stop":1318.507,"duration":14.97},{"text":"The Court of Appeals said, In the case at bar, in addition to the demonstration, by proof or admission of the essential elements of convenience, expense and early trial constituting the interest of justice in the civil case, this criminal case is impressed with the fundamental historical right of a defendant to be prosecuted in his own environment or district.\"","start":1318.507,"stop":1339.289,"duration":20.78},{"text":"Now, the -- the facts which are -- which are admitted or undenied is in Footnote 3 here and they are as follows.","start":1339.289,"stop":1349.43,"duration":10.14},{"text":"A trial in the Eastern District of Illinois would result on unjustifiable increased expenses to petitioner of at least $100,000, undenied, undenied in the record, great inconvenience of witnesses.","start":1349.43,"stop":1362.431,"duration":13},{"text":"I've stated the facts on that to the Court.","start":1362.431,"stop":1365.695,"duration":3.26},{"text":"Serious disruption of business, there be any question about that.","start":1365.695,"stop":1369.879,"duration":4.18},{"text":"We have the transfer records and witnesses and -- and executives and employees all -- from Danville to St. Paul for this protracted trial.","start":1369.879,"stop":1377.881,"duration":8},{"text":"Interferes of contact between petitioners, executives, and as trial attorneys in connection with protract and antitrust prosecution trial, that's the point which I've just argued to the Court.","start":1377.881,"stop":1389.755,"duration":11.87},{"text":"There is no dispute on a single one of these factors that the Court of Appeals found from this record then he -- then they go on.","start":1389.755,"stop":1397.804,"duration":8.05},{"text":"Petitioner has no office, plant or other facility in the Eastern District of Illinois.","start":1397.804,"stop":1403.163,"duration":5.36},{"text":"Well, that of course is undenied.","start":1403.163,"stop":1405.959,"duration":2.8},{"text":"There's no serious congestion of the docket of the District Court of Minnesota.","start":1405.959,"stop":1409.854,"duration":3.89},{"text":"And while a division of the case is pending in the Eastern District of Illinois between the two judges of that district, would've reveal a considerable case load for both of them.","start":1409.854,"stop":1418.193,"duration":8.34},{"text":"The fact is the dockets are current in both districts and -- but judge -- Judge Platt did say that he thought the trial in St. Paul would take a year -- the case would take year longer to come to trial in St. Paul than in Danville.","start":1418.193,"stop":1433.826,"duration":15.63},{"text":"And I submit to the Court that a year for the preparation of a trial of this magnitude is -- is not, in any way, unreasonable.","start":1433.826,"stop":1442.67,"duration":8.84},{"text":"And when the dockets are current, as the Court of Appeals found them to be, it makes no difference.","start":1442.67,"stop":1447.589,"duration":4.92},{"text":"Now, those are the facts upon which the Court of Appeals held that the trial court had abused his discretion aside from the concededly improper factor, had abused his discretion in -- in or denying the transfer of this case.","start":1447.589,"stop":1465.489,"duration":17.9},{"text":"Now, the Government's real point, the Government's real point here is, well, he -- maybe the trial court made a -- was guilty of abuse of discretion, maybe was.","start":1465.489,"stop":1479.114,"duration":13.63},{"text":"But and -- and perhaps, perhaps mandamus is a proper remedy under these circumstances.","start":1479.114,"stop":1484.953,"duration":5.84},{"text":"But they should -- the trial court should have just reversed and sent it back for reconsideration and should not have directed transfer, and I would like to deal with that in the time remaining to me.","start":1484.953,"stop":1501.582,"duration":16.63},{"text":"If Your Honors please, the Government has submitted in -- and as indeed it must, as indeed it must as follows.","start":1501.582,"stop":1513.603,"duration":12.02},{"text":"I'm reading from page 34 of their brief.","start":1513.603,"stop":1516.536,"duration":2.93},{"text":"It would be proper, I'm reversing it for the Court of Appeals to direct transfer if it, Should be clear that without considering the improper factor, reading from Page 34, \"the District Court would've had no alternative but to transfer\".","start":1516.536,"stop":1532.712,"duration":16.18},{"text":"They've said there.","start":1532.712,"stop":1534.452,"duration":1.74},{"text":"That --- that is correct.","start":1534.452,"stop":1535.514,"duration":1.06},{"text":"That's our position.","start":1535.514,"stop":1537.418,"duration":1.9},{"text":"That they say that unless it should be clear that without considering the improper factor, the District Court would've had no alternative but to transfer the direction of transfer should not have been, it should not have been incorporated in the writ.","start":1537.418,"stop":1551.942,"duration":14.52},{"text":"I say to Your Honors that on this record, the Court had no alternative but to transfer if he was going to be, as if he must be in exercising his discretion, if he was going to be governed by the record in this case rather than -- than something else.","start":1551.942,"stop":1568.515,"duration":16.57},{"text":"For the reasons that I've stated, suppose this goes back, suppose this goes back to the District Court as the Government would have, Your Honors, direct to reconsider this matter in the light of the opinion and the present concession of the Government that he had no business going into this fair trial matter.","start":1568.515,"stop":1590.984,"duration":22.47},{"text":"Suppose it did, what could he say as to a reason for holding it in Danville that he has already said?","start":1590.984,"stop":1599.966,"duration":8.98},{"text":"Now, I have a great respect for Judge Platt before whom I've tried a number of cases.","start":1599.966,"stop":1605.061,"duration":5.1},{"text":"But it would be only human, be only human having -- having denied transfer and considered this record as he did for him to say the second time, Oh, well, sure I consider this fair trial in Minnesota business.","start":1605.061,"stop":1622.889,"duration":17.83},{"text":"But that isn't a real thing.","start":1622.889,"stop":1624.614,"duration":1.73},{"text":"I am going to keep this case anyway.\"","start":1624.614,"stop":1627.67,"duration":3.06},{"text":"And I say he couldn't keep it in anyway for any reason that's a substantial reason and no matter what he said, he couldn't controvert the facts that I read to the Court from the opinion of the United States Court of Appeals because there aren't any facts in this record contrary to that.","start":1627.67,"stop":1647.077,"duration":19.41},{"text":"I submit therefore, may it please the Court, that the decision of the Court of Appeals is correct and should be affirmed.","start":1647.077,"stop":1655.671,"duration":8.59},{"text":"Thank you.","start":1655.671,"stop":1659.283,"duration":3.61}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel M. Friedman","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief --","start":1659.283,"stop":1659.969,"duration":0.69}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Friedman.","start":1659.969,"stop":1661.888,"duration":1.92},{"text":"Go ahead.","start":1661.888,"stop":1663.267,"duration":1.38}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel M. Friedman","textObjs":[{"text":"I just like to say briefly in few seconds I have left that it may well be that if any members of this Court were sitting from the District Court in this case, Mr. Chadwell's argument would've been persuasive to them.","start":1663.267,"stop":1677.697,"duration":14.43},{"text":"But we think that contrary to what Mr. Chadwell has said here that there were factors which the District Court reverted to, reverted to.","start":1677.697,"stop":1684.664,"duration":6.97},{"text":"And I might just mention here that one of the things District Court said in the end of his memorandum was he said some facts mentioned by counsel have not been noted in order to like not to lengthen this memorandum.","start":1684.664,"stop":1696.259,"duration":11.6},{"text":"And we think there's no doubt in our mind that when the Court of Appeals in this case did what it did, it was basically substituting it's discretion from the District Court.","start":1696.259,"stop":1706.441,"duration":10.18},{"text":"And it think the clearest demonstration of that is the statement of the Court of Appeals in the next to the last paragraph of it's opinion in page 248 in -- after the stating the things with Mr. Chadwell stated says consequently.","start":1706.441,"stop":1720.826,"duration":14.38},{"text":"We are convinced that this multiple venue criminal prosecution should be tried in the District of Minnesota which is the home of petitioner.","start":1720.826,"stop":1729.765,"duration":8.94},{"text":"But the rule says, the rule says that it should be transferred only if the District Court is satisfied that it's in the interest of justice.","start":1729.765,"stop":1739.765,"duration":10}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Friedman, would you mind listing just precisely and without this argument this -- what Mr. Blanchford did?","start":1739.765,"stop":1749.31,"duration":9.54},{"text":"The things that the -- the judge relied upon to show this was at the interest of justice.","start":1749.31,"stop":1757.051,"duration":7.74}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel M. Friedman","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Mr. Chief Justice, he stated -- I -- I can perhaps put it most effectively if I might read to the Court what Judge Platt himself stated in his response to the rule to show cause in which he said that he had given, this is at page 236 of the record, he said that he gave consideration to all the factors and found several which militated against transfer.","start":1757.051,"stop":1784.707,"duration":27.66},{"text":"The first fact he said that the trial of this case would be delayed at least a year if it were transferred and that --","start":1784.707,"stop":1791.529,"duration":6.82}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Friedman, may ask you -- ask you to read the rest of what the judge said --","start":1791.529,"stop":1795.511,"duration":3.98}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap)","start":1795.511,"stop":1795.604,"duration":0.09}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"-- when he made that statement.","start":1795.604,"stop":1797.749,"duration":2.14},{"text":"I mean in that -- in that (Voice Overlap)--","start":1797.749,"stop":1798.735,"duration":0.99}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel M. Friedman","textObjs":[{"text":"It appeared to respondent that the trial of the case would be delayed at least a year by the transfer and the Government avowed a speedy trial was essential because some of the petitioners, competitors are in financial straights owing to petitioner's alleged conduct and to the fact that petitioner has refused to hold it's allegedly illegal activities.","start":1798.735,"stop":1818.001,"duration":19.27},{"text":"That's the first one.","start":1818.001,"stop":1818.985,"duration":0.98},{"text":"The --","start":1818.985,"stop":1819.701,"duration":0.72}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Where is it?","start":1819.701,"stop":1820.342,"duration":0.64}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel M. Friedman","textObjs":[{"text":"This is at page 236, the paragraph numbered 6.","start":1820.342,"stop":1824.461,"duration":4.12},{"text":"The first one is that transfer of the case would delay at least for a year and that a speedy trial was important because the defendant has allegedly continuing this illegal activity.","start":1824.461,"stop":1834.889,"duration":10.43}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Did the Court state why it was delayed for a year?","start":1834.889,"stop":1839.509,"duration":4.62}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel M. Friedman","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, he -- I assumed he did not stated in so many word but I assume the reason for he said in his previous opinion would delay and I take it that is because of the fact that he had a much smaller dockets than the average --","start":1839.509,"stop":1853.395,"duration":13.89}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that in the (Inaudible) if there is a smaller docket?","start":1853.395,"stop":1855.849,"duration":2.45}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel M. Friedman","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Mr. Justice, that will be set forth.","start":1855.849,"stop":1857.947,"duration":2.1}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"It's alright.","start":1857.947,"stop":1858.398,"duration":0.45},{"text":"That is all I want to know.","start":1858.398,"stop":1859.297,"duration":0.9}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel M. Friedman","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1859.297,"stop":1859.925,"duration":0.63},{"text":"The disagreement between us is as to whether they said there would not be any delay because they say that you average as between all the judges in the District of Minnesota and all the two judges in the Eastern District of Illinois.","start":1859.925,"stop":1873.434,"duration":13.51},{"text":"We say the proper standard for determining how soon you would have a trial before Judge Platt is what the state of Judge Platt's docket wasn't the state of Judge Platt's docket was much better than that of the average docket in the District of Minnesota.","start":1873.434,"stop":1888.281,"duration":14.85},{"text":"Now, the second point -- that was the first point, the second point Judge Platt made was that the Government witnesses maybe inconvenience if forced to travel to the northern city of St. Paul, Minnesota.","start":1888.281,"stop":1899.156,"duration":10.88},{"text":"That's two items.","start":1899.156,"stop":1899.879,"duration":0.72},{"text":"The third one, that the --","start":1899.879,"stop":1900.977,"duration":1.1}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) --","start":1900.977,"stop":1902.871,"duration":1.89}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Alright.","start":1902.871,"stop":1903.545,"duration":0.67},{"text":"You said there's no evidence of that?","start":1903.545,"stop":1905.195,"duration":1.65}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1905.195,"stop":1906.233,"duration":1.04}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel M. Friedman","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, there is.","start":1906.233,"stop":1906.9,"duration":0.67},{"text":"Just the affidavit of Mr. Jenkinson to which I've referred, which states at page 89 that although the Government would not reveal an advance of trial the names of its witnesses, it states that a substantial number of the Government's witnesses live within a 300-mile radius of Danville whereas only one or two of it's presently contemplated witnesses live within 300 miles of St. Paul, they are minor witnesses and that Danville is substantially closer and more convenient for the majority of the Government's key witnesses.","start":1906.9,"stop":1938.555,"duration":31.65}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"No reference to the number?","start":1938.555,"stop":1940.125,"duration":1.57}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel M. Friedman","textObjs":[{"text":"No, there is no reference to the number.","start":1940.125,"stop":1941.939,"duration":1.81}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"How far is Chicago from St. Paul?","start":1941.939,"stop":1944.335,"duration":2.4}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel M. Friedman","textObjs":[{"text":"About it think 350 miles, roughly.","start":1944.335,"stop":1949.228,"duration":4.89}]},{"speakerName":"John T. Chadwell","textObjs":[{"text":"From 350 to 400, an hour by jet plane.","start":1949.228,"stop":1955.881,"duration":6.65}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel M. Friedman","textObjs":[{"text":"Then he referred to the fact that the Government's documents are already in Danville in the custody of the Court.","start":1955.881,"stop":1962.951,"duration":7.07},{"text":"Fourth, and would have to be transferred to St. Paul.","start":1962.951,"stop":1966.698,"duration":3.75},{"text":"Then he stated the transfer would increase the Government's expenses because --","start":1966.698,"stop":1970.935,"duration":4.24}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Let me ask you, did he -- did he comment on the -- the records and documents of the company?","start":1970.935,"stop":1977.999,"duration":7.06}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel M. Friedman","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, he had said, yes, in his earlier opinion, he had recognized that it would a burden on the company to have to transfer its records from St. Paul to Danville.","start":1977.999,"stop":1988.497,"duration":10.5},{"text":"He pointed out that a number of these records were already in the custody of counsel in Chicago but he recognized that there would be an additional burden.","start":1988.497,"stop":1996.909,"duration":8.41},{"text":"He is just at this point.","start":1996.909,"stop":1998.262,"duration":1.35},{"text":"At this point, he is explaining in response to the claim that the difficulties of obtaining the unfair trial where the principal basis for his decision, the other factors he relied on.","start":1998.262,"stop":2009.408,"duration":11.15},{"text":"The point then in the next one is a transfer to increase the Government's expenses because its witness fees would be greater.","start":2009.408,"stop":2015.346,"duration":5.94},{"text":"In other words, the Government has to pay witness fees, mileage witness fees and they would be greater as what its cost to transportation of the Government's staff and then finally it would be more difficult for the Government to get an impartial jury in St. Paul than in Danville.","start":2015.346,"stop":2028.734,"duration":13.39},{"text":"And then over in page 237 in paragraph (7), he pointed out to other factors which suggest the burden on Minnesota Mining would not be as great as they have suggested since a lot of this material deals with rather ancient history would not be present any serious burden on the company to have to take away from it's home office, old records which were not needed for current things.","start":2028.734,"stop":2055.333,"duration":26.6}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":2055.333,"stop":2057.045,"duration":1.71}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel M. Friedman","textObjs":[{"text":"The -- the allegations are basically misuse of patents that they use their patents -- they -- they had these critical patents and that under the threat of actual of threatened patent litigation, they coerced competitors into accepting licenses with a restricted provision.","start":2057.045,"stop":2072.975,"duration":15.93}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. (Inaudible), would you like one minute or so just -- in response to that or -- or not?","start":2072.975,"stop":2078.501,"duration":5.53}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. Attorney General","textObjs":[{"text":"I would just like to point out, if Your Honors please.","start":2078.501,"stop":2080.283,"duration":1.78}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2080.283,"stop":2081.266,"duration":0.98}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. Attorney General","textObjs":[{"text":"And I appreciate your suggestion.","start":2081.266,"stop":2084.971,"duration":3.7},{"text":"That the -- the first statement delayed at least a year is not supported by the record.","start":2084.971,"stop":2091.978,"duration":7.01},{"text":"He just -- even the Court said that, no doubt in good faith thinking that would be true.","start":2091.978,"stop":2095.741,"duration":3.76},{"text":"I don't question that at all.","start":2095.741,"stop":2097.07,"duration":1.33}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"There's nothing in the record or anything?","start":2097.07,"stop":2098.426,"duration":1.36}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. Attorney General","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Your Honor.","start":2098.426,"stop":2100.347,"duration":1.92},{"text":"Then he went on and accept -- accepted as true, denying us the presumption of innocence that a speedier trial in that was needed because of -- because of avowal of the Government that we're continuing these patent activities which are under attack.","start":2100.347,"stop":2116.306,"duration":15.96},{"text":"This second point, the Government's witnesses maybe inconvenienced, I've already dealt with it.","start":2116.306,"stop":2121.297,"duration":4.99}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, you've dealt it.","start":2121.297,"stop":2122.13,"duration":0.83}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. Attorney General","textObjs":[{"text":"Third point on the documents I have, and the transfer would increase the Government's expenses, my answer to that is that -- that is of no significance and as --because of the home district point and because of the facts found without contradiction to which I refer to my arguments, I think --","start":2122.13,"stop":2140.397,"duration":18.27}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":2140.397,"stop":2141.574,"duration":1.18}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. Attorney General","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2141.574,"stop":2141.73,"duration":0.16}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":2141.73,"stop":2151.124,"duration":9.39}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. Attorney General","textObjs":[{"text":"I beg your pardon--","start":2151.124,"stop":2152.284,"duration":1.16}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":2152.284,"stop":2161.96,"duration":9.68}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. Attorney General","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, there were two statements in the record on that and that's all.","start":2161.96,"stop":2168.31,"duration":6.35},{"text":"And if I'm not correct on this, I would like Mr. McGee to -- to correct me.","start":2168.31,"stop":2172.273,"duration":3.96},{"text":"One was that there are two letters written that deal with sales or purchases of the products involved in the indictment in the Eastern District of Illinois.","start":2172.273,"stop":2185.443,"duration":13.17},{"text":"Of course, there were hundreds of thousands of sales of these products of all over the United States.","start":2185.443,"stop":2189.446,"duration":4}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Including this?","start":2189.446,"stop":2190.729,"duration":1.28}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. Attorney General","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, but that I -- we --","start":2190.729,"stop":2192.075,"duration":1.35}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"But in the record (Inaudible)","start":2192.075,"stop":2196.647,"duration":4.57}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. Attorney General","textObjs":[{"text":"No question but the business we do in this district is minimal.","start":2196.647,"stop":2200.667,"duration":4.02},{"text":"And it -- it may give venue, as I argue to you -- to the Court.","start":2200.667,"stop":2204.067,"duration":3.4}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":2204.067,"stop":2205.813,"duration":1.75}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. Attorney General","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, because it is -- it is nothing com -- excuse me, I didn't mean to interrupt the Court.","start":2205.813,"stop":2210.824,"duration":5.01}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":2210.824,"stop":2212.821,"duration":2}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. Attorney General","textObjs":[{"text":"It's minimal compared to the home district to which we are -- to which we move the transfer of the case.","start":2212.821,"stop":2219.158,"duration":6.34},{"text":"That is where --","start":2219.158,"stop":2220.206,"duration":1.05}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap)","start":2220.206,"stop":2221.619,"duration":1.41}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. Attorney General","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir, and in terms of witnesses, in terms of convenience of trial.","start":2221.619,"stop":2225.905,"duration":4.29}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":2225.905,"stop":2235.494,"duration":9.59}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. Attorney General","textObjs":[{"text":"We sell -- we sell tape.","start":2235.494,"stop":2237.486,"duration":1.99},{"text":"We sell tape all over the United States.","start":2237.486,"stop":2239.773,"duration":2.29},{"text":"And the -- the tape that it's in -- that we do sell all over the United States is sold in Danville as well as St.Paul, New York, Washington and everywhere else.","start":2239.773,"stop":2248.316,"duration":8.54}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":2248.316,"stop":2253.45,"duration":5.13}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. Attorney General","textObjs":[{"text":"I haven't the slightest idea, Your Honor.","start":2253.45,"stop":2255.392,"duration":1.94},{"text":"I -- I will say that I have frequently wondered why they bring suits where -- where they do.","start":2255.392,"stop":2259.843,"duration":4.45},{"text":"In this case, I don't know why.","start":2259.843,"stop":2261.719,"duration":1.88},{"text":"I have no idea why.","start":2261.719,"stop":2262.79,"duration":1.07}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":2262.79,"stop":2265.53,"duration":2.74}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. Attorney General","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, they won -- they won several down there and I think that maybe a reason why although I don't want to state that as -- as my view necessarily.","start":2265.53,"stop":2275.694,"duration":10.16},{"text":"The A&P case I might say was in Danville.","start":2275.694,"stop":2278.105,"duration":2.41}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"General Motors?","start":2278.105,"stop":2279.458,"duration":1.35}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. Attorney General","textObjs":[{"text":"The General Motors --","start":2279.458,"stop":2280.331,"duration":0.87}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":2280.331,"stop":2282.036,"duration":1.7}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. Attorney General","textObjs":[{"text":"Judge Lindley is not there any longer.","start":2282.036,"stop":2284.61,"duration":2.57},{"text":"That -- that trial was in Danville.","start":2284.61,"stop":2287.388,"duration":2.78},{"text":"There have been some other cases in Danville.","start":2287.388,"stop":2290.292,"duration":2.9},{"text":"That's the only protracted antitrust case tried in Danville so far as I know.","start":2290.292,"stop":2294.453,"duration":4.16}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":2294.453,"stop":2295.897,"duration":1.44}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. Attorney General","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir, he's the only one in Danville.","start":2295.897,"stop":2297.49,"duration":1.59},{"text":"There are two judges in the Eastern District.","start":2297.49,"stop":2299.423,"duration":1.93},{"text":"Judge Jergens is in East St. Louis and Judge Platt is in Danville.","start":2299.423,"stop":2303.392,"duration":3.97}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":2303.392,"stop":2307.739,"duration":4.35}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. Attorney General","textObjs":[{"text":"Has he tried any?","start":2307.739,"stop":2309.326,"duration":1.59},{"text":"He has not tried any contested antitrust cases to the best of my knowledge.","start":2309.326,"stop":2314.055,"duration":4.73},{"text":"He has had a number of antitrust cases in which there'd been settlements.","start":2314.055,"stop":2319.904,"duration":5.85}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":2319.904,"stop":2322.565,"duration":2.66}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. Attorney General","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir, that was tried in -- in St. Louis.","start":2322.565,"stop":2324.803,"duration":2.24}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":2324.803,"stop":2325.108,"duration":0.31}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. Attorney General","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, yes, he's --","start":2325.108,"stop":2325.989,"duration":0.88}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":2325.989,"stop":2328.795,"duration":2.81}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. Attorney General","textObjs":[{"text":"To -- to Minnesota -- St. Paul, Minnesota which is the home district of the defendant.","start":2328.795,"stop":2333.267,"duration":4.47}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":2333.267,"stop":2335.961,"duration":2.69}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. Attorney General","textObjs":[{"text":"Four, yes, sir.","start":2335.961,"stop":2338.111,"duration":2.15}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"How large is the district?","start":2338.111,"stop":2339.535,"duration":1.42}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. Attorney General","textObjs":[{"text":"How large is the district?","start":2339.535,"stop":2340.596,"duration":1.06}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"The whole state.","start":2340.596,"stop":2341.207,"duration":0.61}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. Attorney General","textObjs":[{"text":"The whole state, yes, sir.","start":2341.207,"stop":2342.964,"duration":1.76}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":2342.964,"stop":2347.64,"duration":4.68}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. Attorney General","textObjs":[{"text":"They -- they hold court in various places, yes, sir.","start":2347.64,"stop":2350.63,"duration":2.99},{"text":"The -- they hold court, both in St. Paul and in Minneapolis and in other areas in the State.","start":2350.63,"stop":2356.966,"duration":6.34}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":2356.966,"stop":2362.413,"duration":5.45}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. Attorney General","textObjs":[{"text":"No, it's -- it's distributed around among the judges, the cases are and I might say to the Court --","start":2362.413,"stop":2369.023,"duration":6.61}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"But you don't know (Inaudible)","start":2369.023,"stop":2370.914,"duration":1.89}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. Attorney General","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, no, no, no, and -- and I might -- and --and that wasn't the reason that were -- we've made a motion to transfer.","start":2370.914,"stop":2379.864,"duration":8.95},{"text":"No, no, we don't know and the -- and the fact is that the jury can be drawn from all over the State for any one of the areas.","start":2379.864,"stop":2391.77,"duration":11.91},{"text":"Although generally speaking, it's gone from the general proximity of (Inaudible)","start":2391.77,"stop":2396.048,"duration":4.28}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":2396.048,"stop":2401.684,"duration":5.64}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. Attorney General","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I believe that's right, Your Honor.","start":2401.684,"stop":2404.01,"duration":2.33},{"text":"I believe it is.","start":2404.01,"stop":2405.962,"duration":1.95},{"text":"They hold court in other areas in the State and I'm not too sure about -- about that.","start":2405.962,"stop":2412.058,"duration":6.1},{"text":"I must say that I perhaps not given the Court exact information on that.","start":2412.058,"stop":2415.292,"duration":3.23}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":2415.292,"stop":2424.757,"duration":9.47}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, of course.","start":2424.757,"stop":2425.711,"duration":0.95}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":2425.711,"stop":2426.886,"duration":1.18}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, of course.","start":2426.886,"stop":2429.148,"duration":2.26},{"text":"We do have -- Mr. McGee has called my attention to the affidavit of Mr. Hunt (ph) which appears beginning on page 70 of our -- of the transcript which deals with this subject.","start":2429.148,"stop":2447.322,"duration":18.17},{"text":"Thank you, Your Honor.","start":2447.322,"stop":2448.331,"duration":1.01}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Warren Court","arguedOn":"Jan 9, 1964","petitioner":"Platt","respondent":"Minnesota Mining & Manufacturing Company","docket":"113","citation":"376US240(1964)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/376/240","lowerCourt":"United States Court of Appeals for the Seventh Circuit","grantedOn":"","decidedOn":"Mar 9, 1964"}